Here's a multi-form question based on the StackExchange documentation:

Question: In a LaTeX document using the biblatex-sbl style, you want to prevent the bibliography from replacing repeated author names with a dash (———). Which of the following code snippets, when added to your preamble, would correctly achieve this?

A) \renewcommand{\bibitemsep}{1\baselineskip}

B) \AtBeginBibliography{\renewbibmacro{dashcheck}[2]{#2}}

C) \PassOptionsToPackage{authordate}{biblatex-chicago}

D) \setlength\bibindent{\parindent}

Correct Answer: B

Explanation: Option B is the correct answer. The code \AtBeginBibliography{\renewbibmacro{dashcheck}[2]{#2}} specifically targets the dash replacement feature in the biblatex-sbl style. It redefines the dashcheck macro to always use the full citation (#2) instead of replacing it with a dash.

Option A (\renewcommand{\bibitemsep}{1\baselineskip}) only changes the spacing between bibliography entries and doesn't affect the author name replacement.

Option C (\PassOptionsToPackage{authordate}{biblatex-chicago}) is related to the biblatex-chicago package and doesn't address the dash replacement issue in biblatex-sbl.

Option D (\setlength\bibindent{\parindent}) only sets the indentation for the bibliography and doesn't affect the author name replacement.

